2025-05-30 09:20:27,256 - copilot_service - INFO - --------------------------------------------------
2025-05-30 09:20:27,256 - copilot_service - INFO - 
Flashcard 6:
2025-05-30 09:20:27,257 - copilot_service - INFO - Question: Can an NP-hard problem be in NP?
2025-05-30 09:20:27,257 - copilot_service - INFO - Answer: Not necessarily. An NP-hard problem may not be in NP. For example, the Halting Problem is NP-hard but is undecidable and not in NP.
2025-05-30 09:20:27,257 - copilot_service - INFO - --------------------------------------------------
2025-05-30 09:20:27,258 - copilot_service - INFO - 
Flashcard 7:
2025-05-30 09:20:27,258 - copilot_service - INFO - Question: What is the Halting Problem?
2025-05-30 09:20:27,258 - copilot_service - INFO - Answer: The Halting Problem is a classical problem that asks whether a given Turing Machine T halts on a given input string w. It is known to be undecidable and unsolvable.
2025-05-30 09:20:27,259 - copilot_service - INFO - --------------------------------------------------
2025-05-30 09:20:27,259 - copilot_service - INFO - 
Flashcard 8:
2025-05-30 09:20:27,259 - copilot_service - INFO - Question: What are the two steps to show that a problem L is NP-complete?
2025-05-30 09:20:27,260 - copilot_service - INFO - Answer: 1) Show that L is in NP (i.e., solutions can be verified in polynomial time). 2) Show that an NP-complete problem (like Satisfiability) can be reduced to L in polynomial time.
2025-05-30 09:20:27,260 - copilot_service - INFO - --------------------------------------------------
2025-05-30 09:20:27,260 - copilot_service - INFO - 
