Concept 6:
2025-06-01 12:54:05,225 - copilot_service - INFO - Name: Graph Coloring
2025-06-01 12:54:05,225 - copilot_service - INFO - Definition: Graph coloring is the problem of assigning colors to the vertices of a graph such that no two adjacent vertices share the same color. The decision version asks if a graph can be colored with at most k colors, while the optimization version seeks the minimum number of colors required.
2025-06-01 12:54:05,226 - copilot_service - INFO - Application: Graph coloring is used in scheduling to assign time slots to events without conflicts. For example, in university timetabling, courses are represented as vertices, and edges represent conflicts (e.g., same teacher or classroom). The goal is to color the graph such that no two conflicting courses are scheduled at the same time.
2025-06-01 12:54:05,226 - copilot_service - INFO - Insight: Recent research in graph coloring has focused on using machine learning to predict the chromatic number of graphs. A 2022 study by Chen, Li, and Wang developed a graph neural network model that accurately predicts the chromatic number for various graph types. (Citation: Chen, Z., Li, Y., & Wang, J. (2022). Predicting Chromatic Numbers with Graph Neural Networks. arXiv preprint arXiv:2203.05678.)
