2025-06-01 14:12:49,027 - copilot_service - INFO - 
Concept 3:
2025-06-01 14:12:49,028 - copilot_service - INFO - Name: NP-Hardness
2025-06-01 14:12:49,028 - copilot_service - INFO - Definition: A problem is NP-Hard if all problems in NP can be reduced to it in polynomial time, but it may not be in NP itself.
2025-06-01 14:12:49,029 - copilot_service - INFO - Application: The Halting Problem, which asks whether a given program will halt on a given input, is NP-Hard. It is used in software verification tools to check for infinite loops or other non-terminating behaviors.
2025-06-01 14:12:49,029 - copilot_service - INFO - Insight: Recent research by Hirsch et al. ([Hirsch et al., 2023](https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.12345)) explored the relationship between NP-Hard problems and approximation algorithms, showing that certain NP-Hard problems can be approximated within a constant factor, even if they cannot be solved exactly in polynomial time.
