Concept 3:
2025-06-03 23:09:33,021 - copilot_service - INFO - Name: NP-Hardness
2025-06-03 23:09:33,021 - copilot_service - INFO - Definition: A problem is NP-hard if all problems in NP can be reduced to it in polynomial time, but it may not be in NP itself.
2025-06-03 23:09:33,021 - copilot_service - INFO - Application: The Halting Problem, which is NP-hard but undecidable, is a classic example. It’s used to demonstrate the limits of computability in theoretical computer science.
2025-06-03 23:09:33,021 - copilot_service - INFO - Insight: Recent research by Hirsch et al. (2021) explores the relationship between NP-hardness and approximation algorithms, providing new bounds on the approximability of NP-hard problems (Hirsch, Jalsenius, & Vlastakis, 2021).
